<Document>
<name>Sea-to-Sky Highway</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Sea-to-Sky Highway</h2><p><i>British Columbia, Canada · BC-99, West Vancouver to Pemberton</i></p><p><b>From sea-level fjord with bald eagles to alpine resort country in 90 minutes.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>116 km (72 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>2–3 hrs</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>Year-round (winter for skiing; spring–fall for hiking)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Weekend traffic jams, weather (wet most of the year), winter snow above Squamish, occasional rockslides</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>179</td></tr></table><hr><p>Substantially upgraded for the 2010 Olympics — this is the rare scenic highway that's also a fast modern road. You can do Vancouver to Whistler in under 90 minutes, but you'll want to take longer. From sea level on Howe Sound (one of North America's southernmost fjords, with bald eagles wintering by the thousands at Brackendale) to alpine resort country at Whistler. Multiple roadside waterfalls, a granite monolith second in size only to Yosemite's El Capitan, and a former copper mine you can drive into. Continue past Whistler to Pemberton and on to Joffre Lakes for one of the great alpine hikes.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Britannia Mine Museum</b> — Once the largest copper mine in the British Empire (closed 1974). Tour the gravity-fed mill building (a 20-story step structure on the mountain) and ride a mine train into a tunnel.</li><li><b>Shannon Falls</b> — 335 m, third-tallest in BC. 5-minute walk from the parking lot to the base.</li><li><b>Stawamus Chief</b> — 700 m granite monolith — second-largest free-standing in the world (after El Capitan in Yosemite). Climbers visible from the highway. 3-summit hike for those willing to suffer.</li><li><b>Brackendale eagle viewing</b> — World's largest concentration of wintering bald eagles — 1,000+ counted on a single January day, drawn to the salmon runs. Dec–Feb only.</li><li><b>Brandywine Falls</b> — 70 m drop into a basalt amphitheater. Short walk from parking; a must-stop.</li><li><b>Joffre Lakes (past Pemberton)</b> — Three turquoise glacial lakes stacked up a moraine, accessed by 5–10 km hike. Day-pass reservations required May–Oct.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
